<definition xml:id="lecture-notes-definition-operations-on-functions">
  <title>Arithmetic Operations on Functions</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> be functions.
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>The <term>sum</term> of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>, denoted <m>f+g</m>, is given by
            <me>(f+g)(x)=f(x)+g(x)</me>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>The <term>difference</term> of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>, denoted <m>f-g</m>, is given by
            <me>(f-g)(x)=f(x)-g(x)</me>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>The <term>product</term> of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>, denoted <m>fg</m>, is given by
            <me>(fg)(x)=f(x)\cdot g(x)</me>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>The <term>quotient</term> of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>, denoted <m>\frac{f}{g}</m>, is given by
            <me>\left(\frac{f}{g}\right)(x)=\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}</me>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>


<exercise xml:id="lecture-notes-example-3-symbolic-combinations" workspace="2in">
  <title>Performing Arithmetic Operations on Functions</title>
  <statement>
    <p>For the functions <m>f(x)=5-x</m> and <m>g(x)=x^2-3x</m>, find the following functions.</p>
    <p>
      <ol>
        <li><p><m>(f+g)(x)</m></p></li>
        <li><p><m>(f-g)(x)</m></p></li>
        <li><p><m>(fg)(x)</m></p></li>
        <li><p><m>\left(\frac{f}{g}\right)(x)</m></p></li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>


<theorem xml:id="lecture-notes-theorem-domains-of-functions">
  <title>The Domains of Sums, Differences, and Products of Functions</title>
  <statement><p>
<ul>
    <li>
          <p>The domain of <m>f+g</m>, <m>f-g</m>, and <m>fg</m> consists of all elements common to the domains of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>.</p>
    </li>
    <li>
       <p> 
     The domain of <m>\frac{f}{g}</m> consists of all elements common to the domains of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>, excluding any <m>x</m> for which <m>g(x)=0</m>.
  </p>
    </li>
</ul>
</p></statement>
</theorem>


