<definition xml:id="lecture-notes-def-composition">
  <title>Composition of Functions</title>
  <statement>
    <p>Let <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> be functions.</p>

    <p>
      The <term>composition</term> of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>, denoted <m>f\circ g</m>, is given by
      <me>(f\circ g)(x)=f\big(g(x)\big)</me>
      There are two additional definitions that are associated with composition.
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p><m>g(x)</m> is called the <term>inner function</term> since it appears inside the input of <m>f(x)</m>.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><m>f(x)</m> is called the <term>outer function</term> since it appears outside the input of <m>g(x)</m>.</p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>


