<theorem xml:id="lecture-notes-thm-hlt-implies-inverse-is-function">
  <title>Theorem</title>
  <p>Any function that passes the horizontal line test has an inverse that is also a function.</p>
</theorem>


<corollary xml:id="lecture-notes-remark-notation-inverse-function">
  <title>Notation for an Inverse Function</title>
  <p>If the inverse of <m>f(x)</m> is a function, we denote it by <m>f^{-1}(x)</m>.</p>
</corollary>


<note xml:id="lecture-notes-warning-inverse-vs-reciprocal">
  <title>Warning</title>
  <p><m>f^{-1}(x)\ne \frac{1}{f(x)}</m>. If we want the reciprocal, we write <m>[f(x)]^{-1}=\frac{1}{f(x)}</m>.</p>
</note>


